    "sectionsText": "Key Learning Points ◆ EXISTS checks if at least one row exists in the subquery ◆ NOT EXISTS ensures NO rows exist in the subquery ◆ The subquery is CORRELATED — it references outer query fields ◆ EXISTS is often more efficient than LEFT JOIN + NULL check ◆ EXISTS stops scanning as soon as one match is found | CDS Source Code ",
    "detailsText": "EXISTS vs JOIN: ┌──────────────┬───────────────────────────┬─────────────────────┐ │ Scenario │ EXISTS │ JOIN │ ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────┼─────────────────────┤ │ \"Has at least│ EXISTS + correlated subq │ JOIN + DISTINCT │ │ one XXX\" │ (stops on first match) │ (processes all rows)│ │ \"Has no XXX\" │ NOT EXISTS (can use index) │ LEFT JOIN + NULL │ └──────────────┴───────────────────────────┴─────────────────────┘ USE CASES: EXISTS: Find travels that have at least one 'New' (N) booking NOT EXISTS: Find travels that have NO 'Accepted' (B) bookings"
